00:22:41,785 --> 00:22:46,528
is an extension, is sort of a container for me to project my sense of agency into.

409
00:22:47,289 --> 00:22:50,912
And meanwhile, part of the experience is defined as being not me,

410
00:22:51,893 --> 00:22:53,994
as being the environment, as being an enemy.

411
00:22:54,795 --> 00:22:58,878
And the funny thing is here, like the trick that the game designers are pulling off without even realizing it,

412
00:22:59,078 --> 00:23:01,540
is that the player is actually controlling the whole thing.

413
00:23:02,315 --> 00:23:06,417
If you jump, it's not that Mario jumps up, you're also pushing the world down.

414
00:23:06,897 --> 00:23:11,779
There's this awesome trick that happens so naturally where the player projects their identity into your avatar.

415
00:23:12,640 --> 00:23:17,682
So wherever we, as game designers, use our mechanics or our stories to draw a boundary,

416
00:23:18,002 --> 00:23:23,545
we invite the player's existing habits of separation to see themselves reflected in that boundary.

417
00:23:24,257 --> 00:23:27,218
And I think there are really, really, really cool subversive ways to do this.

